1
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:31,700
Rules: In an N×N grid, click one button, and the light on that cell and the lights around it flip at the same time.

2
00:00:31,700 --> 00:00:38,900
Goal: Start from all dark and turn on all lights (or start from all bright and turn off all lights).

3
00:00:38,900 --> 00:00:47,800
Click the same button twice is the same as not clicking it.

4
00:00:47,800 --> 00:00:58,600
If you click buttons in a different order, the final lights are the same.

5
00:00:58,600 --> 00:01:05,600
So, for each button, we only care “press” or “not press”, and we don’t care about order.

6
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:13,100
We can show buttons and lights as two separate groups: one group is the button states, the other group is the light states.

7
00:01:13,100 --> 00:01:23,800
Our goal is: find one set of buttons, so that the lights become all on. So how do we find such a button set?

8
00:01:23,800 --> 00:01:36,500
There are 2^(N×N) button sets for N×N buttons, and each set gives one unique light state. We can just try all sets and see the light state.

9
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:49,500
For example, when N=2, the number is 2^(2×2)=2^4=16. We can list all cases fast and get the answer.

10
00:01:49,500 --> 00:02:02,033
For example, when N=3, the number is 2^(3×3)=2^9=512. We can still brute force all cases and get the answer.

11
00:02:02,033 --> 00:02:15,633
For N=5, the classic case, the number is 2^(5×5)=2^25=33,554,432, so we need a computer.

12
00:02:15,633 --> 00:02:29,033
When N=6, the number is 2^36=68,719,476,736. It grows too fast, and even a computer is hard to use.

13
00:02:29,033 --> 00:02:38,433
So what should we do? Is there a faster and smarter way?

14
00:02:38,433 --> 00:02:48,833
If you look carefully, you will find: no matter the start, we can press buttons row by row, and light as many lights as we can.

15
00:02:48,833 --> 00:02:57,733
For example, we press some buttons in row 1 at random. Now some lights in row 1 are on, some are off.

16
00:02:57,733 --> 00:03:05,333
To make row 1 all on, we can press the matching buttons in row 2 under the lights that are off.

17
00:03:05,333 --> 00:03:14,433
Now some lights in row 2 are off. Because pressing row 2 will change row 1, we instead press buttons in row 3.

18
00:03:14,433 --> 00:03:26,033
Repeat this until we finish the last row. If the last row becomes all on, then we found a solution.

19
00:03:26,033 --> 00:03:30,933
Here some lights are still off, so this is not a correct solution. Let’s try another one.

20
00:03:30,933 --> 00:03:38,033
This time, let’s press the first two buttons in row 1.

21
00:03:38,033 --> 00:03:46,033
After we keep going down, the last row becomes all on, so this is a correct solution.

22
00:03:46,033 --> 00:03:57,733
From row 2 on, each row’s presses are decided by the row above. So we only need to try all press ways of row 1, and see the last row.

23
00:03:57,733 --> 00:04:10,900
With this row link, we keep randomness only in row 1, and the search drops to 2^N. Here, among 32 ways, we found 4 solutions.

24
00:04:10,900 --> 00:04:20,633
This is still exponential. So is there a faster and nicer way?

25
00:04:20,633 --> 00:04:29,633
For an N×N grid, our basic moves are only N×N kinds: press or not press one button.

26
00:04:29,633 --> 00:04:40,033
For one light, only a few nearby buttons can change it. For example, the top-left light is only changed by the three buttons near the top-left.

27
00:04:40,033 --> 00:04:49,433
Pressing many buttons is like adding many moves together. We add these three moves to get the state of light 1.

28
00:04:49,433 --> 00:04:55,633
Is there a way to add moves so that only one light changes?

29
00:04:55,633 --> 00:05:04,633
If every light can be turned on alone, then we can add those moves and make all lights on.

30
00:05:04,633 --> 00:05:12,833
Now, look again at a 3×3 grid. There are 9 moves, call them move 1 to move 9.

31
00:05:12,833 --> 00:05:20,233
Look at light 1. Here, move 1 and move 2 both flip light 1.

32
00:05:20,233 --> 00:05:27,433
Now we add move 1 onto move 2, then move 2 will not flip light 1 anymore.

33
00:05:27,433 --> 00:05:35,933
Also, move 4 flips light 1, so we add move 1 onto move 4 too.

34
00:05:35,933 --> 00:05:41,633
Now only move 1 can flip light 1.

35
00:05:41,633 --> 00:05:45,033
Next, look at light 2.

36
00:05:45,033 --> 00:05:53,633
In moves 2 to 9, find the moves that flip light 2, and add move 2 onto them.

37
00:05:53,633 --> 00:06:01,533
Here, move 2 does not flip light 2, so we swap move 2 and move 3.

38
00:06:01,533 --> 00:06:08,533
Then we add move 2 onto move 4 and move 5.

39
00:06:08,533 --> 00:06:18,033
Repeat this, and we can make sure move n can only flip lights n to 9.

40
00:06:18,033 --> 00:06:27,733
Since move 9 cannot flip lights 1 to 8, and can only flip light 9, we now have a move that flips only light 9.

41
00:06:27,733 --> 00:06:35,433
Then we go back to move 8. Luckily, move 8 can flip only light 8.

42
00:06:35,433 --> 00:06:43,133
Now look at move 7. Move 7 flips light 7 and light 9 together.

43
00:06:43,133 --> 00:06:50,133
We can add move 9 onto it, so move 7 flips only light 7.

44
00:06:50,133 --> 00:07:00,833
Let’s keep adding for the remaining moves.

45
00:07:00,833 --> 00:07:06,433
In the end, we get moves that can flip only light 1 to only light 9, one by one.

46
00:07:06,433 --> 00:07:16,133
Now we add these 9 moves together, and we get a solution for the game.

47
00:07:16,133 --> 00:07:22,333
Let’s look again at the 3×3 grid.

48
00:07:22,333 --> 00:07:34,633
In fact, we can put all buttons and lights into one long line. Then buttons and lights form a 9×9 big matrix.

49
00:07:34,633 --> 00:07:48,133
It is easy to see: what we did is Gauss elimination on this matrix. By adding one row to another, or swapping two rows, we make it an upper triangle matrix.

50
00:07:48,133 --> 00:07:59,633
Then we go backward and turn it into the identity matrix.

51
00:07:59,633 --> 00:08:13,433
Finally, add all rows, and we get one full set of a solution.

52
00:08:13,433 --> 00:08:25,033
For a 5×5 grid, we can do the same. We build the button-light matrix, then do elimination on it.

53
00:08:25,033 --> 00:08:31,067
We add the 25 moves together, and this is one solution for 5×5.

54
00:08:31,067 --> 00:08:43,467
You can see: in the eliminated matrix, in the last two rows, the light part is blank. That means these two moves flip no lights. We call them silent moves.

55
00:08:43,467 --> 00:08:50,767
We combine them in pairs, and get 4 silent moves.

56
00:08:50,767 --> 00:09:02,667
Silent moves do not change lights, so we can add them onto the solution we found. This matches the 4 solutions from the first-row brute force method.

57
00:09:02,667 --> 00:09:15,067
Because silent moves exist, at least two press ways give the same light state. So some light states can never be made, like “flip only the first light”.

58
00:09:15,067 --> 00:09:27,000
Buttons change nearby lights, and lights are changed only by nearby buttons too. So the final light state can be written as adding some buttons, that is, all on.

59
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:39,767
Before, we did elimination on the button-light matrix, which is like multiplying by an inverse matrix at the same time. Now we do the same row moves on the light vector, and we get the button states, that is the solution.

60
00:09:39,767 --> 00:09:52,667
Since the light vector is all on, matrix times vector is the same as adding all press ways. With this, we do not need the inverse matrix; we can get the solution directly by elimination.

61
00:09:52,667 --> 00:10:04,267
Because there are N×N lights and N×N buttons, and each row adds N×N buttons, the cost is (N×N)^3 = N^6.

62
00:10:04,267 --> 00:10:17,167
This is polynomial time, but the N×N matrix is still big. Can we find an even faster and smarter way?

63
00:10:17,167 --> 00:10:29,367
Just now, we added buttons and lights as a whole, not by rows. But from the first-row method, once we fix row 1 buttons, we can get the last row lights.

64
00:10:29,367 --> 00:10:37,600
Can we mix the adding method and the first-row method, and use row 1 buttons to write the last row lights directly?

65
00:10:37,600 --> 00:10:49,200
From the first-row method: lights are decided by nearby buttons, and the next row buttons are the flips of the lights. We list one row of lights alone, and write it by buttons.

66
00:10:49,200 --> 00:10:58,100
For example here, the first row on the left means light 1 is decided by button 1 and 2, and the blue cells mean the button is the flip of the light.

67
00:10:58,100 --> 00:11:09,000
Note: “add then flip” is the same as “flip one part then add”. So we can list the flip part alone.

68
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:19,600
Also, if one button is added twice, it is the same as not adding it. Same for lights: flip twice is the same as no flip.

69
00:11:19,600 --> 00:11:30,100
Next, we derive row 2. It is decided by adding the button states from the row above. Since flips can be listed alone, it is also decided by adding the flip states of the lights.

70
00:11:30,100 --> 00:11:38,600
Here we show the first button and the first light in row 2. Each is an add or a flip of the row above buttons or lights.

71
00:11:38,600 --> 00:11:43,200
Then we derive the rest.

72
00:11:43,200 --> 00:11:52,300
So, starting from row 1 button states, we can keep deriving, and get which row 1 buttons are added to make the last row lights.

73
00:11:52,300 --> 00:12:02,800
At last, we get a matrix like the adding method. But now, both lights and buttons have only N items.

74
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:10,500
Because lights are flipped during the derivation, the final light vector is also a flipped state.

75
00:12:10,500 --> 00:12:21,800
Now we do elimination on the matrix, and do the same row moves on the light vector, and we get the row 1 button states.

76
00:12:21,800 --> 00:12:32,500
You can see: after elimination, it is like the 25×25 case: the last two rows are silent moves, and the light vector on the right is the solution.

77
00:12:32,500 --> 00:12:45,800
To get silent moves, we need the inverse matrix. If you like, you can try it. In fact, because the matrix is very symmetric, the column vectors here are the same as the silent moves.

78
00:12:45,800 --> 00:12:56,400
It is easy to see: like the adding method, the matrix size drops from N×N to N, so the cost is N^3.

79
00:12:56,400 --> 00:13:09,000
In the first-row adding method, we need the matrix that links row 1 buttons and last row lights. We must derive it, and its cost is N^3.

80
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:22,100
We derived each light one by one, but these lights are linked. After we reorder the matrix, we can see it has strong symmetry.

81
00:13:22,100 --> 00:13:31,600
If you look carefully, you can find: for each cell, the number of states in its up/down/left/right neighbors is always even.

82
00:13:31,600 --> 00:13:41,200
Since we only need the last matrix, we only need the first row of the last matrix, and we can derive the rest.

83
00:13:41,200 --> 00:13:51,300
So we only need to derive the first light’s state, and we can get all lights’ states, and lower the cost.

84
00:13:51,300 --> 00:14:03,900
We found: for 5×5, because there are two silent moves, together with the earlier solution, we get 4 solutions.

85
00:14:03,900 --> 00:14:13,700
For 3×3, because there are no silent moves, the solution is unique.

86
00:14:13,700 --> 00:14:24,900
So for an N×N grid, what is the max number of silent moves? Now we look at 4×4, and use the first-row adding method.

87
00:14:24,900 --> 00:14:37,200
This time we find, by surprise, all buttons are canceled, and we get a zero matrix. That means 4×4 has 4 independent silent moves, and together they give 16.

88
00:14:37,200 --> 00:14:52,733
Because row 1 has only 16 states, all 16 are silent moves. Here, any row 1 press way can remove all lights by using the last three rows.

89
00:14:52,733 --> 00:15:03,967
Also, these 16 silent moves match 16 solutions. Here too, from any row 1 press way, we can light all lights by using the last three rows.

90
00:15:03,967 --> 00:15:13,867
Because row 1 has at most 2^N states, an N×N grid has at most 2^N solutions.

91
00:15:13,867 --> 00:15:27,100
Here are the cases from N=1 to N=16. This list is in OEIS as A159257.

92
00:15:27,100 --> 00:15:37,500
For the rank of this matrix, we can use the formula above.

93
00:15:37,500 --> 00:15:52,700
We talked about how many solutions there are, but we did not prove a solution always exists. For a normal Lights Out game, does a solution always exist?

94
00:15:52,700 --> 00:16:05,100
In fact, if the game meets two rules, then it is solvable.

95
00:16:05,100 --> 00:16:13,400
This is not only for square grids. In fact, Lights Out with any shape and layout is solvable.

96
00:16:13,400 --> 00:16:23,000
If the grid is not one connected piece, then separate parts do not affect each other. So we can solve each connected part on its own.

97
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:30,900
Next, I will use a simple way, with math induction, to prove all Lights Out games are solvable.

98
00:16:30,900 --> 00:16:41,500
First, look at cases with only 1, 2, or 3 buttons. Here are all possible layouts, and they are clearly solvable.

99
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:49,000
Now, for a 2×2 grid, remove one cell each time, and we get 4 grids with 3 buttons.

100
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:55,500
Let’s solve these 3-button grids, then add the removed cell back.

101
00:16:55,500 --> 00:17:05,800
If, for any added-back cell, the number of buttons around it is odd, it will be lit. Then this solution is a solution for 4 buttons.

102
00:17:05,800 --> 00:17:14,100
Sadly, for all added-back cells, the number of buttons around them is even, so none of these cells are lit.

103
00:17:14,100 --> 00:17:23,000
Now, let’s try to add these 4 states together. You can see all lights are lit this time.

104
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:38,400
This is because: in each of the 4 cases, 3 lights are flipped, so after adding, each of the 4 lights is flipped 3 times. Since 3 is odd, all lights flip to on.

105
00:17:38,400 --> 00:17:46,300
This is the 2×2 solution, and this method works for any game with an even number of buttons.

106
00:17:46,300 --> 00:17:57,300
Then what about a game with an odd number of buttons? Let’s look at 3×3, and assume we know solutions for all 8-button games.

107
00:17:57,300 --> 00:18:06,900
Like before, we remove one cell, solve it, then add it back. Here, in all 9 cases, the added-back cell is still not on.

108
00:18:06,900 --> 00:18:16,600
We add them together. Since each light is flipped an even number of times, all lights are off.

109
00:18:16,600 --> 00:18:23,000
To fix this, we can first press the center button, and flip 5 lights.

110
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:31,400
Then we add the press ways of the four corners, one by one. Now all lights are flipped.

111
00:18:31,400 --> 00:18:42,300
This is because: the corner press ways are like “flip all lights” first, then “flip one light”. Since the total flips are even, it is the same as flipping 4 single lights.

112
00:18:42,300 --> 00:18:49,200
So we exactly make up the even number of lights we did not flip before, and we turn on all lights.

113
00:18:49,200 --> 00:19:02,100
It is not hard to prove: in any Lights Out game, there is always some move that flips an odd number of lights, so we can use this idea to solve odd-button games.

114
00:19:02,100 --> 00:19:08,700
So we proved: for any number of buttons, we can always find a solution.

115
00:19:08,700 --> 00:19:17,400
In fact, this proof can be written in formal language.

116
00:19:17,400 --> 00:19:27,800
Also, this proof is closely linked to graph theory.

117
00:19:27,800 --> 00:19:35,700
To find faster solutions, we can try to think from these directions.

118
00:19:35,700 --> 00:20:00,000
The creator is limited, so if you have better ideas or ways to do it, please share in the comments!

